title: What a new Supreme Court means for abortion
CommentTitle:
I don't think that abortion is about a women's right to choose. It's about the question at which point the foetus is a human being. And there is no scientific answer to that. Most people would agree that in the beginning, when it's only one cell, it's not a human being, and most people would agree that the moment before the baby gets born, it is already a human being. But at which point exactly we say now it's a human being is hard to find. I think we could says when the heart starts beating, although I admit that it is objectively seen a relatively arbitrary point and it's more of an emotional thing that I would say that it becomes a human at that point. Furthermore does the embryo already look very human relatively early during the pregnancy, so I don't really know either at which point it should be limited.

Also I think there is generally nothing wrong with putting restrictions on it, though you need to look into every single restriction to see which ones are bad or good. For example the one with the ultrasound picture of the foetus. I think that is a good thing. Nobody forces them to see the picture, they are simply asked if they want to see it, and I think you should look at the thing you are about to "kill" (I used it for lack of a better word).

The more important steps tho to decrease the numbers of abortion are sex ed, teaching kids more about protection and increasing access to protection

title: Why beef is the worst food for the climate
CommentTitle:
"Don't eat beef." 
Hindus: You know I am somewhat of an environmentalist myself.

title: Why beef is the worst food for the climate
CommentTitle:
You could do sequel to episode about crops that require the most water. We have many places in the world that have had or are facing zero days. In Australia, we have a '"water buyback" scheme for the Murray-Darling Basin (Australia's food bowl. Which stretches from Queensland through NSW all the way to Victoria). It was meant to be a way of balancing the use of water by limiting the volume of water that farmers could extract from the river. The government 'buys back' water entitlements from growers, thereby reducing the amount of water taken from the river. 

Now you don't need to be a farmer to own water entitlements, in fact the Chinese and the US are the biggest investors in our water entitlements. The government was caught paying $80 million of tax payers money to company that is registered to the Cayman Islands.

Last year during our summer (which is very dry) water stopped flowing in the rivers causing large blue-green algae blooms which starved oxygen to all the fish. Millions of fish were killed and seen floating in the river. While there was a drought and lot of finger pointing on to blame, what we need to remember is that the basin can only support so much. Why are we growing things like cotton, chestnuts and rice? Things that require so much water. We should be growing things that suit our climate. This is why a follow up video to this one but about water usage I think is important for people to know.

title: Steve Rattner: Inflation subsided and median incomes are up
CommentTitle: Data be damned. My finances are much tighter than they were three years ago. Housing costs are much higher, the car we recently bought cost 50% more than the car we bought a few years ago despite being very similar in miles/years, groceries are still WAY more expensive, as is eating out (fast food/restaurants are nearly 2x up from 3 years ago) - which we're doing a LOT less of. And when we do eat out, instead of enjoying it I feel stressed and guilty over how much it costs. Gas is... close to where you would expect it had we not experienced COVID inflation, but it's still not where it should be. We used to have enough extra money to save up and go on an out of state/country vacation every 1-2 years, but we haven't been able to do that the past three years. So in spite my income going up about 17%, it's been more than negated by the rise in the cost of living. We SHOULD be doing better than ever. And yet, we're not. If they can't get some serious downward pressure on cost of living prices, people will continue to be historically disgruntled. Both the lower and middle classes are being squeezed harder than ever, being taken advantage of, and Congress isn't stepping up to help us, and we all see it and recognize it.

title: Sen. Booker blasts GOP: ‚ÄòMorally obscenity‚Äô of child poverty is a ‚Äòpolicy choice‚Äô
CommentTitle:
Following the WWII two obvious things were moved into national legislation.

The first was that farmers historically would over produce and then go broke. It was also obvious that surplus crop production was essential as a hedge against emergencies. It takes up to 2 years to "change course" on farm production.

So, farmers gained a price support system. They were paid to not grow certain crops in some years, and paid to grow surplus in other years. The surplus food was rotting in the fields. This price "support" stabilized production a bit over market need, and avoided bankrupt farmers if prices collapsed. Harvesting the surplus was the next logical step. This was the origin of the Federally supported School Lunch programs in 1946. (These replaced 1930s programs abandoned during the war.)

In the 1950s the now obvious idea was to give poor people access to that surplus food that was being grown, and tossed. The solution was to give poor people "food stamps" they could use to buy food that would otherwise be left to rot. Their health was improved, farmers were more financially secure, and the surplus production capacity was maintained. That was the origin of food stamps under the administrations of Truman, and also expanded under Eisenhower. In 1969 the Nixon administration expanded the program again, and added some restrictions to eligibility. This was the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP). 

The new SNAP food stamps cost us nothing extra from the existing agricultural production price controls. The school nutrition programs cost us nothing extra from the existing agricultural production price controls.

NOTHING! Farmers would be paid regardless.

The Republican urge to return to the Bad Old Days is not merely cruel, it is destructive.

title: 'Hamas is worse than ISIS': Senior Advisor to PM Netanyahu
CommentTitle: It is tragic that any Palestinians or Israelis have died . Everyone who is objective needs to consider the following (a} no Palestinian lives would have been lost or injured but for the decision of Hamas to massacre over 1200 Israelis with almost all of them being civilians and (b) even after the massacre Hamas knew it could avoid the loss of Palestinian lives by being willing to return the 100-150 hostages in return for a ceasefire prior the even the first Israeli air strike . Hamas was fully aware that Israel would be required to respond with air strikes and blockades and moreover that this would result in a far great loss of life of their own people as compared to returning the hostages.  They also knew that to continue holding the hostages would force Israel into a ground operation which would result in the loss of more Israeli and Palestinian lives.  AGAIN -  no Palestinians had to die if Hamas had slaughtered Israelis . AGAIN- even with that no Palestinians had to die if Hamas returned the hostages in return for a ceasefire.  Hamas chose to keep the hostages rather than value the lives of the residents of Gaza . Those who try to defend the conduct or condone the loss of Israeli lives by making claims regarding past Israeli conduct always selectively omit the fact that it always arose after Hamas had engaged in terrorist attacks ( suicide bombings etc ) and the firing of rockets which led Israel to respond with air strikes and blockades. If there were no rockets being fired at Israeli towns and cities then Israel would not have had to conduct air strikes and blockades. It is very telling that those that try to rationalize or condone the actions never express a wish that there could be peace or state that it is sad that any civilians died . Consider that in the last 15 years Hamas received billions of dollars to buy rockets from Iran then consider if Hamas had used those billions to better the lives of the residents of Gaza rather than buy rockets ( again keep in mind if no rockets are fired at Israeli towns and cities then no air strikes or blockaded ).  None of the actions of Hamas over the past 15 years have bettered the lives of residents of Gaza but rather it has led to deaths of thousands of their own people and led to the worsening of the conditions for the living.  To really understand the conduct of Hamas an objective person has to look at their mission goal which is the eradication of Israel. They refuse to accept the right of Israel to exist even within the confines of the 1948 borders ( which Israel offered to the Palestinians numerous times in the 1980s). Accordingly , Hamas does not care that their actions lead to a great loss of life to the residents of Gaza because they are not interested in peace and sadly they see their own civilians deaths as grist for the PR mill . The reason they would not give the hostages back is very simple ‚Äì they wanted to have Israel launch a ground invasion because they want more dead on both sides so that the cycle of war and hate continues rather than having a peace since that would mean having to accept Israel .  Those that choose to condone the actions of Hamas with respect to the events of the past week obviously have no moral compass nor do they support any idea of peace or desire any peace that does not involve the eradication of Israel .  Unlike them, I do mourn the loss of the lives of Palestinian civilians and wish that the leaders and supporters of Hamas valued the lives of those civilians more than killing Israelis /Jews and chose to spend money bettering the lives of those people rather than buying rockets. Indeed, the one thing that they accomplished ( which was certainly deliberate) is to make it impossible for any Israeli government for at least a generation to discuss peace ‚Äì which is what they want ‚Äì because they want the cycle of hate and death to continue. NOTE ‚Äì I support a 2 state peace agreement =I believe most Israelis would be willing to do that just as they did in the 1980s.

CommentTitle:
The ACA is a step in the right direction, but until we have Universal Healthcare, it's not enough.

I think it's crystal clear that Article 3 does not apply for running for President. There is a clear distinction that both President and Vice-President is left OUT as "cannot hold office" from Article 3.
It list Congressperson and Senator and Elector of President and VP.  But it does NOT list Office of the President.
See there are some clear distinctions here. A Congressperson and Senator is elected INSIDE a State. Not Federally (Nationally). Same with "Electors". But the President is elected NATIONALLY by all people. Not the states. So it's the "will of the people" that come into play here.
The 14th Amendment was designed so STATES cannot influence the government which is federal. That is how the civil war insurrection even came about. 

It's ridiculous to make the claim that the "office of USA" is what applied to "President'. It's literally an ELECTED position. "Officer of USA" can be appointed. Also why would the highest office be listed as a "Side-note" Like "officer of USA". It's silly.

They left it open, that technically a person even one that was involved in the insurrection back then could separately run for President and then the PEOPLE decide nationally.  They would account for every citizen which even the people in the southern states are a part of is a citizen and hence have the right to vote.

No one has even been charged with insurrection. So how can you even label it other than "It's what I feel like" opinion.

Local states should not be able to decide national federal elections. It disenfranchise voters. And ironically that is what article 3 actually protects when it comes to FEDERAL election of PRESIDENT.
There is a big distinction with congress and Senate since they are elected IN a state not by the citizens of all states.

Leave it to a Canadian to interpret and explain US Constitution, lol.

title: ‚ÄúViolently shaking, thrashing:‚Äù Witness details first ever nitrogen gas execution
CommentTitle: I grasp that some behaviour in society is completely unacceptable and that the rest of society should not be accountable financially for enabling that behaviour whether incarcerated or not. That does not mean that we have to be brutal about curtailing that behaviour.  I had a much-loved dog.  She lived to be twenty years old in human years which is quite a feat.  Her legs started to cave. I could see in her an embarrassment and sort of a shame that she could no longer support her body to go out to pee or poo.  I had to let her go for both her dignity and mine.  I was with her when she left this world.  It was calm and peaceful.  She simply went limp, and she was gone.  The point of this long text is that if veterinarians have worked out dignified euthanasia then why can we not extend the same care to people for reasons we don't understand cannot be part of a disciplined society?  We do not have to sink to the level of a perpetrator to end the perpetration of agony.

But, for him to claim that the poking of the needle for failure to find a vein intravenously and then intramuscularly and "excruciating poking from the needles" was inhumane?? He stabbed a woman to death! He never fully accepted his capital sentence. As the AG put it, "he gamed the system for as long as he could," prolonging his life until HE chose the nitrogen gas method. Presumably, he didn't think he would get his choice approved due to his prior "botched" execution, let alone by a never-before-tested method. But, the state used his own defense attorneys' expert witness on euthanasia against him, the expert claiming, "it's a humane way to die!" He also held his breath as long as he could and was told only to drink clear liquids an hour or so before the execution. He didn't eat all day then ate Waffle House smothered in A1, so that he could get sick and choke on his vomit and not breathe in nitrogen, so that it would look inhumane and someone would step in. They knew he was going to be doing this. Unsurprisingly, during his final statement, there was no mention of the victim and no apology to the victim's friends and family or the courts. title: Authors of 'The Big Fail' on what the U.S. learned from the COVID-19 pandemic
CommentTitle:
What is the basis for saying that school closings were a disaster? That children ended up falling behind in their education? FFS, this was a once in a century event, where we didn't know what to do to save lives. One surefire way to keep people well is to not let them be exposed to the virus. Children will catch up on what they didn't learn, and they'll be alive to do it. 
Even if it was assumed that they were healthier and more resilient, the people they might have carried the virus home to might not have been. The teachers who needed to be in the classroom, and adults they might have exposed to the virus, might have been part of a compromised population.
As for claims that their mental health suffered, there's no way to determine what caused those problems. They were exposed to the fear surrounding the virus, the horrendous polarization over what was the proper way to handle it. They lost family: aunts, uncles, cousins, grand and great grand parents, even friends. Many of their homes had parents who took opposite stances on what was the right thing. Home were full of conflict.  - to say nothing of other political issues parents fought over. Separate from the virus, the country was angry like we've never seen it.

But I remember Texas, where ambulances would have to drive a hundred miles to find an open slot in an ER. I remember Alaska, where there simply weren't enough ERs. Sure, we could have continued the business as usual approach, but I remember pyres of burning bodies in India, right? Stories of people there being sent home to die, even though less-crowded ERs may have been able to save their life.

title: ‚ÄòBiden has 9 months to tell the story‚Äô: The struggle to reach voters on the economy
CommentTitle:
The whole question is the definition of "economy" and whether or not anyone else's "economy" or financial condition makes any difference to most Americans any more.  After all, Ronald Reagan never asked, "Are people whom you don't know and there's no reason for you to care about better off than they were four years ago?"  He asked, "Are YOU better off than YOU were four years ago," implying that as long as enough Americans were doing well to elect him, neither they nor he had to actually do anything to help those being left behind compete with those who had already made it.  Lest we forget, he won with 50.7% of the popular vote in 1980 and didn't score a landslide victory until 1984 when the unemployment rate was more than twice what it is today, based on his grandfatherly smile, his cutting remarks dripping with sweetness and a chuckle, and a slogan of "Morning in America," not so different from Trump's "MAGA."

Americans have been taught for the last 45 years that the only economy that counts is their own.  Carter tried to sell a modest lifestyle instead of acquisitiveness to the American voter in 1980 to help the country weather the oil shock storm of stagflation and got his head handed to him on a platter.  As a result, even Bernie Sanders explains his proposals in terms of money ($30/hr minimum wage, not going bankrupt due to education or health costs, etc.) rather than what the right thing to do for one's fellow Americans is.

As a result, if you like eggs and the price of eggs goes up, it is taken by some to mean that the president is trying to make their life difficult.  By the way, compared to 1982, when Reagan was president, eggs now cost all of 8¬¢ more per dozen, adjusted for inflation.  And yet because the price may be higher than four years ago, people who think this way say, "My economy is terrible," and then ignore the financial condition of everybody else, whom they've been taught not to care about.  If gas goes up in price, how many of those complaining (forgetting about who is responsible for the price increase) switch to car-pooling, thereby giving up privacy and 20 minutes of sleep, or to public transportation?  "I don't want to have to ride with the kinds of people who use public transport every day."  Whose fault is what you want?  The president's?  Why is what you want any more important than what someone else wants? ¬†

Now, if you want to ask why Musk or Bezos don't have to car-pool, why they deserve the fairy-tale lives they have, you have a good question to pose to either of them, or any other super rich person.  You never hear anyone debate Bezos, Musk, etc. on why they think they deserve hundreds of billions of dollars in wealth and a firefighter who saves lives and property doesn't.  (No, I am not a firefighter.)

That's why Biden has trouble communicating the state of the economy to many people.  Those people want him to do something about the state of _their_ economy, though Biden was elected to be president of the USA, not the president of only Joe, Jane and Cindy Schlabotnick or Laverne Bleppy and her kids. Besides, the law does not allow one man to centrally control the economy.  I thought Republicans knew that.

CommentTitle:
Removing the right to a speedy trial is the problem not the cash bail. The courts wrongly ruled you can wave your right and made speedy trials so speedy the defense could not prepare making almost everyone wave their right. 

So defendant waives their right they then can hold them forever in effect. 

We need to make it the defense not the prosecution that chooses when to go to trial. Prosecution most of the time should be ready to go anytime they charge someone especially for a lot of the crimes these folks involved with there just not that much evidence eather way to require months to prepare. In many cases only days needed. 

Of course attorney for defense should be drafted from the pool of lawyers. not the overwhelmed public defenders and even the best must put in say a third of their time into free defenses. So all defendants get a lawyer who is obliged to give them a good amount of their time starting immediately. Make qualifying as a defense lawyer part of getting one's law license. 

Someone who has so few friends and family or personal savings to put up the small bail amounts often involved does have something wrong in their mental make up that requires mental health care even if they don't want it. 

Take away cash bail fewer return for trial or prison. But with above reforms it will be months at most not year. And Progressives can put their money where their mouth is and set up foundations to give out the bail money. Want to correct pay day loans Progressives should set up non profit check cashing organizations I think they will find the high rates are at least half it not 3/4 justified on basis of how much the poor default. 
Bans on loans to the poor result in the Mob doing it, this a case it a demand that must be met.

CommentTitle:
I"m looking at a lot of empathy literature, and having tough conversations with people on the other side. I think Al Franken NAILED this interview in this respect, giving Lindsey the space to say what he wanted without interjecting and overtalking. It's a VERY difficult skill to master, LISTENING when you don't like what the other person is saying. 
I respect both of these men for having a civil conversation-- Lindsey for coming onto the show, and Al for having the grace to let Lindsey speak his mind freely. 
Both were very reserved in this respect.

My reaction to my mom when she says ‚Äúoh honey, people have been complaining about the weather and declaring the world was going to end since they invented language.‚Äù 
Just because previous generations had crises they survived does NOT mean this crisis is survivable. There is a tipping point when it gets hot enough our forests will die, and when that happens our planet will suffocate. We act like the damage we are doing is reversible, and will always remain so. But Climate change is a cascading disaster- each problem makes the other problems worse. The earth is not something we can rebuild if it collapses.

title: Ukraine War Is Exposing Racial Disparities in Refugee Treatment | The Daily Show
CommentTitle:
My distant cousin had gone to Ukraine to study medicine and are one of the many Indian students who got stuck there. The colleges first threatened these kids by telling them they would cancel their admission if they were to leave the country but eventually had to close down when things started getting bad. When she and her peers tried to flee, they overcame many obstacles while crossing borders. The people managing them told to their face that the Ukrainians were getting a preference to get out. All these kids are trying to do is board a flight back home, not to stay and get integrated into their society. What's the excuse now?

She reached Hungary safely 1-2 days ago, so don't worry, but her whole experience there was just heartbreaking.

Then I had kids.  One who remembered threatening me with children for saying something they didn't like asked me after, "not like you expected, huh?'

Some people think kids change you.  Others were realists and knew what to expect.

title: What Michael Kosta Learned About Guns From Switzerland - After The Cut | The Daily Show
CommentTitle: Switzerland is not gun crazy. The United States is gun crazy. I'm American and I've lived in Switzerland since 1990. I don't have a gun. I don't know anyone who has a gun. Switzerland does have a military. It has an army and an Air Force. It is a militia. People are not automatically given a rifle when they turn 18. It is not an all volunteer military. Men must serve in the Army for a number of weeks every year until they are sometime in their 50s, or they have the possibility to do Civil Service instead. Women can also join the military. Women are not obligated to do so. I don't know all of the specifics. When a person is in the military, yes they are given a rifle that they must keep at home when they are not doing their service. It cannot be loaded and it must be disassembled and locked away until needed.

title: What Michael Kosta Learned About Guns From Switzerland - After The Cut | The Daily Show
CommentTitle: I love the post on guns here in Switzerland, but some things in this speech are not quite accurate: no one automatically gets a gun on their 18th birthday, and of course we do have an army. Maybe that's the reason for the confusion: every Swiss man has to join the army and women are free to do so. There, of course, most soldiers are armed and we generally take these weapons home with us. All adults have the right to own weapons, but we need a gun license to do so - but we are not allowed to carry them on us, only when we go to a shooting range or to the military. Weapons must also never be loaded when they are not in use. The ammunition is stored safely. There have also been no shootings in the Swiss parliament. The attack was aimed at the parliament of the canton of Zug, which is a federal state. Bad enough, but that wasn't precisely mentioned in the report either.

title: What Michael Kosta Learned About Guns From Switzerland - After The Cut | The Daily Show
CommentTitle:
"I'd like to address the abundance of misinformation in the comments; it's quite astonishing. I'm a Swiss citizen and a gun owner who has served in our militia. When you reach the age of 18 in Switzerland, you are required to join the Army. Approximately 50% of males choose to enlist, although there are alternative options like civil service.

Upon commencing military service, we are provided with a rifle. After completing our service and fulfilling our duties as reservists, we have the option to retain our firearms, typically between the ages of 30 and 35. To retain ownership, one must obtain an official gun ownership license, which is easily attainable as long as there are no criminal records.

Yes, we are allowed to keep ammunition at home, provided we have the necessary gun license. However, strict regulations mandate secure storage, usually in a safe or a similar secure space.

Currently, only a fraction of individuals choose to keep their firearms after their service ends, roughly around 11%. This is a departure from the past when the numbers were higher.

While Switzerland does have a significant gun culture with various events centered around firearms, it's important to note that it doesn't compare to the gun craze in the United States.

Additionally, Switzerland grants its citizens considerable freedom when it comes to firearm ownership. This includes the right to possess fully automatic weapons, red dot sights, and suppressors for civilian enthusiasts.

One crucial point to mention is that you cannot casually carry a firearm in public, let alone openly. When heading to a shooting range, it's required to transport your firearm without any ammunition loaded. Ammunition may be carried separately, but only when you're en route to a shooting range or engaged in hunting activities

This will increase the chances of lost/stolen guns getting repatriated and will make tracking guns involved in crimes faster and easier than a serial number through a vitiated ATF. And no possessor of a stolen gun is going to want to tag it, so hot guns will get even hotter. And if anyone is found with a gun not bearing their name and/or one that tracks back through the serial # to a gun reported stolen, questions will be asked. Maybe by a judge.

CommentTitle:
As a German I can tell you its not as easy as it seems to be. Of course the money still has to be earned somewhere and all of that (Health care, education) is being paid by the tax payers. When I go to the doctor and I leave without payment, its just I paid already with my health insurance which is mandatory. For me thats around 300$ each month and I also pay for the health insurance of the unemployed. 

It doesnt bother me personally even tho I would like to pay less taxes. But I came from a poor family and still was able to go to university because someone else paid for me. Thats why I dont mind paying for someone elses education. 
Its kinds like an unwritten contract between the people. ‚ÄûI pay for you when you are in need and you pay for me when I am in need‚Äú. I dont think its unreasonable to dislike that idea. Its selfish, but not entirely unreasonable. But since americans talk so much about how much they love their country and repeating tirelessly that USA is the best country in the world, they truly dont care that much for their fellow citizens. I could never agree to a system which leaves someone hungry, sick or uneducated just because they dont have enough money.

title: U.S. Men Are Suffering A 'Friendship Recession'
CommentTitle:
As a Disabled 25 year old progressive man who grew up in a red district with a TBI and was homeless half my childhood it's hard to find people who can relate to me. Especially in my city. Probably the best friend I've ever had is my Therapist. Like when I try to develop a friendship I wanna talk about what goes on in the world and what's bugging us about it. Being a progressive in a red district makes it extrememly hard to have a civil conversation with someone in person or even online. For example I told someone here my favorite musician and they went into a whole Pizza Gate conspiracy theory about the musician. When I said that was false there was friction and anger towards me. 

I also like to talk about past and present struggles and get to know how people think. (I want to become a Therapist and genuinely find people interesting) I'll offer my basic opinions and possible advice but always tell them I'm not a licensed therapist. When and if they want to ask about my life they seem intimidated by the time I'm done talking. And I often never hear from them again. Many people are intimidated by thought provoking questions and life probing questions which is understandable. They have every right not to answer any of my questions. But I find it that oftentimes people have no problem answering my questions. But it's when they ask me about my past they start to lose interest in who I am. Much of my life has been a series of unfortunate events. Those who have stayed in my life often ask how I keep going. Sometimes those who I stopped hearing from due to what I can only assume is intimidation will message me randomly after months or even  years of not talking to me just to ask me how well my life is going. When I update them on the good the bad and the ugly they reply with, "Man that sucks I hope things get better but at least this good thing happened to you. I just want you to know you truly are an inspiration to me man. For you to live through all that and keep going it's amazing." Then there are people who assume my whole life is a lie and try to defame me towards my friends even though I have evidence for most of the things I've been through. I guess in a world full of lies someone being completely open about their life is the scariest thing of all even if what they tell you about their life is the truth.

title: U.S. Men Are Suffering A 'Friendship Recession'

I'm 38 and my tight knit friends from High School and College are either moved away or we don't communicate as much.  Many of them are considered family by myself and my wife as well.  However, it is very hard to make new "lifelong" friends.  I have many acquaintances, but it is hard to turn it into a close friendship, you know like the ones you developed when you were younger.  We all like each other, have similar interests, kids the same age, and enjoy hanging when we do.

Those early relationships and bonds are formed and last a long time because when you are younger you and the people around you are going through "life's shit" at the same time and that builds lifelong bonds vs now when you are older, you are not usually experiencing and growing in life with those friends anymore, so instead you have to settle for a long term playmate.

title: Labor Leader BODIES Suggestion That UAW Strike Would Hurt Economy
CommentTitle: From 1998 to 2001, I worked for Delphi in a plant in Moraine Ohio. Every quarter plant management would have these (we called them) "We-Suck" meetings. Basically the plant was shut down for an hour each shift, all the workers herded into the auditorium where most of management (including the plant manager) was already assembled. They'd give a run-down of exactly WHY we sucked, and, without directly saying it out loud, it was all our (the workers) fault, complete with graphs and charts (supposedly) showing where we were sucking (how much being paid out for wages/insurance/benefits, how much scrap loss, how LITTLE actual production, etc.). One quarter the meeting started off with an introduction to our new plant manager. He led off with a slide-show; pictures of his company-paid-for car, his company-paid-for house, the private school the company was paying for his kids to attend, etc. (All this "company-paid-for" was not an assumption by the workers. The guy came out and said it almost EXACTLY like that). Then the standard "We-Suck" meeting commenced.

It would be nice to be able to have civilised discussions about involuntary mental health treatment. I don't agree with 99% of what Eric Adams says and does, for example, but his point about involuntary mental treatment shouldn't be thrown out with the bathwater. If people won't get off the street when it's below freezing, are unable to manage their own camping area to the point that hoarded items contribute to fires, or as Anna says, are smoking meth on public transit, shouldn't those behaviors be considered within the  "danger to self/others" standard of most psychiatric admissions?

title: Why Progressives Downplay Crime & Homelessness
CommentTitle:
I consider myself pretty liberal on most issues, and I have never just "accepted" street homelessness. It is inhumane towards the individual and is a blight on American cities.

On social media, I have always advocated for much more affordable housing than currently exists, livable wage laws, more outdoor sanctioned camping places, more _humanely-run_ emergency shelters and more drug addiction and mental health treatment access. I always get nasty "feedback" from conservatives stating that the homeless should simply be arrested. When I then point out how much more tax money would be spent in prosecuting, hiring court-appointed defense attorneys and jailing those who are convicted who cannot pay fines would be than with my ideas, they fall silent.

Of course it shouldn't be legal to shoot up drugs on the streets. People who do this need to be directed towards treatment facilities that will allow them to shoot up there, while _strongly encouraging_ them to get into drug withdrawl treatment.

Homelessness is certainly one cause of crime that shouldn't be ignored. It is also true that some cities in the US with relatively low levels of street homeless have high levels of crime.

I live in Seattle and don't see the crime that FoxNews tries to project on liberal areas.  In fact, the theft rates in Seattle are actually slightly lower than in my "low crime", conservative midwestern hometown.  And violent crime rates are lower in Seattle than most conservative states. title: FBI Arrests Autistic Teen After HELPING Him Join ISIS. Was It Entrapment?
CommentTitle:
Entrapment as a legal defense requires that a reasonable person, could be convinced to take an illegal action, when prompted to do so by someone else. If the subject has time to think about their actions, prepare for the action, then it's showing that they would likely have committed the crime, even without the prompt. 

A famous example was the dateline to catch a predator, they faced issues with the first season where a lot of the people featured on the show claimed entrapment. So they changed the format of the show, that they would ask them to bring something specific for the "victim" they would request alcohol, snacks and condoms. The logic is, a reasonable person going out their way to stop off somewhere to buy, condoms alcohol and snacks, is motivated enough to do the thing that was prompted. The prompt was no longer seen as entrapment, because they had plenty of time to think about their course of action and change their mind.

I'm lucky enough to live in the UK. We have problems and our NHS also has issues thanks to our current government - but no one has to worry about money when getting much needed healthcare for themselves and their family. Healthcare is free to access paid by taxes. We never have to worry about paying for a doctor visit, emergency room visit or calling an ambulance (even though they currently take hours to arrive sometimes - which we're hoping to fix at the next election). Prescribed medications are free for children, elderly, those on low incomes and people with certain chronic illnesses. And no matter how many medications you are on, even if you work, you can buy a pre payment certificate for the equivalent of about 15 dollars a month (not sure about the exchange rate) to cover all an individual's prescription medications.

We're fighting to keep our system and to stop it being turned into yours. You deserve a healthcare system that works for everyone  and you need to fight for a better type of health care for you and your family. Health should not be dependent on wealth. Access should be equal and affordable for everyone everywhere.

title: Study Reveals Climate Change NIGHTMARE May Now Be Inevitable
CommentTitle:
The Co2 is now 417 ppm.  In 1856 a scientist studied CO2 and its concentration, and surmised that if it should rise, the Earth would warm. Climate change became "a thing" in 1988 when the CO2 level was 350 and humans were emiting 22 gigatons and increasing at a rate of about 0.3 to 0.4 GT per year. Since then glacier and permafrost have been melting and temperatures rising. CO2 is now 417 ppm and emissions are 36 GT and increasing still increasing.  Though a freezer door is no longer opened wider than it already is, once it is open to any extent, thawing will continue.  Similarly, we can slow down emissions or even stop them, but the door to global warming (CO2 above 300-350 ppm) has already been breached, and we can't unbreach it.¬†
Anyone under 40 years old will live long enough to curse the birth of the CEO's of the fossile fuel industry, car industry and the (mostly conservative) political leaders who allowed this to happen. In fact the whole climate change debate for the last 30 years has demonstrated the cognitive derangement that is modern conservatism.  :_(

title: 1 Killed, 20+ Injured In Chief's Super Bowl Parade Shooting
CommentTitle: I'm local and lived in one of the most violent neighborhoods in KC, MO. I did not go a night without hearing a volley of gunfire. When we first moved to the city in 2017 I would call shots fired to 911 every time I heard them so almost nightly. The dispatcher always asked me the same thing. "Can you see if anyone is hit?" When I said no then I would never even see KCPD.  One night I was woken up by someone actively trying to kick in my door. I immediately contacted 911 and it took police who's station is less than a mile from me 45 mins to get there and they had no sense of urgency. I had just moved into that home and whomever was kicking the door in did not know me. Since we are forced to be very aware that we are expected to stop them ourselves the door they were attempting to kick in had a kick block that likely saved me and my two children from being in a home invasion.  We had a murder every weekend. The KCPD are reactive not proactive especially in black and brown neighborhoods. 2 weeks ago I moved into the suburbs with my children and we havent heard one shooting. Ppl get murdered here weekly and no one is ever caught. Or when they are caught especially caught with a weapon they are usually linked to several other shootings. We had a guy recently wait outside a bar with an Ar15 and sprayed the crowd as ppl left during last call. When they got that rifle and tested it they matched it to 3 other homicides. KCPD needs a complete overhaul.  As many told me in my old neighborhood.  "Pd never comes to help us they just come to arrest us " there is also a deep mistrust to LE for good reason. We just aren't the KCPDs priority.
